  "prompt": "How do you determine the pH of hydrofluoric acid?",
  "response": "Determining the pH of hydrofluoric acid (HF) involves understanding its dissociation in water and using the concept of equilibrium. HF is a weak acid, and it only partially dissociates in water:\n\n\\[ \\text{HF} \\rightleftharpoons \\text{H}^+ + \\text{F}^- \\]\n\nHere are the steps to determine the pH:\n\n1. **Determine the concentration of HF**: Let\u2019s say the concentration of HF is \\( C \\) mol/L.\n\n2. **Write the expression for the acid dissociation constant (Ka)**: The dissociation constant for HF is given by:\n\\[ K_a = \\frac{[\\text{H}^+][\\text{F}^-]}{[\\text{HF}]} \\]\n\nFor HF, the \\( K_a \\) value is approximately \\( 6.6 \\times 10^{-4} \\).\n\n3. **Set up the equilibrium expression**: At equilibrium, let \\( x \\) be the concentration of \\( \\text{H}^+ \\) ions formed. So, the concentrations will be:\n\\[ [\\text{H}^+] = x \\]\n\\[ [\\text{F}^-] = x \\]\n\\[ [\\text{HF}] \\approx C - x \\]\n\nSince HF is a weak acid and dissociates only slightly, we can approximate that \\( [\\text{HF}] \\approx C \\).\n\n4. **Solve for \\( x \\)**:\n\\[ K_a = \\frac{x \\cdot x}{C - x} \\approx \\frac{x^2}{C} \\]\n\nTherefore,\n\\[ x^2 = K_a \\cdot C \\]\n\\[ x = \\sqrt{K_a \\cdot C} \\]\n\n5. **Determine the pH**:\n\\[ [\\text{H}^+] = x = \\sqrt{K_a \\cdot C} \\]\n\nThe pH is given by:\n\\[ \\text{pH} = -\\log [\\text{H}^+] \\]\n\nSo,\n\\[ \\text{pH} = -\\log \\left( \\sqrt{K_a \\cdot C} \\right) \\]\n\n6. **Substitute the values**: Suppose the concentration \\( C \\) of HF is 0.1 M. Then,\n\\[ [\\text{H}^+] = \\sqrt{6.6 \\times 10^{-4} \\cdot 0.1} = \\sqrt{6.6 \\times 10^{-5}} \\approx 8.1 \\times 10^{-3} \\]\n\nTherefore, \n\\[ \\text{pH} = -\\log (8.1 \\times 10^{-3}) \\approx 2.09 \\]\n\nThis is how you determine the pH of hydrofluoric acid. Note that for more accurate results, especially at higher concentrations, you may need to solve the quadratic equation without approximating \\( [\\text{HF}] \\approx C \\).",
